00–Male":"1100–Overleden","1105–Female":"1105–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1105":"1105","before 1100":"vóór 1100","1100":"1100","Abt 1105":"circa 1105","1075":"1075","1150":"1150","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Europe":"Europa","Poorstock, Bridport, Dorset, England":"Bridport, Dorset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"–":"Deceased","1075–1150":"1075–1150","1100–Male":"1100–Deceased","1105–Female":"1105–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1105":"1105","before 1100":"before 1100","1100":"1100","Abt 1105":"about 1105","1075":"1075","1150":"1150","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Europe":"Europe","Poorstock, Bridport, Dorset, England":"Bridport, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Arundel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","(of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>arondel</i> ‘little swallow’ (a diminutive of <i>arond</i> ‘swallow’, from Latin <i>hirundo</i>).","habitational name from a place so named in West Sussex, from Old English <i>hārhūne</i> ‘horehound’ (a wild plant, <i>Marrubium vulgare</i>) + <i>dell</i> ‘valley’. This place is the seat of the dukes of Norfolk. In northern England, folk etymology resulted in variants such as   Arendale  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Arrindell","meanings":["West Indian (Dutch Caribbean and the Dominican Republic): probably an altered form of English   Arundel  ."]},{"name":"Arrendale","meanings":["English: variant of   Arundel  ."]},{"name":"Arendale","meanings":["English: variant of   Arundel   2."]},{"name":"Arendall","meanings":["English: variant of   Arundel  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Robert de Arundel married Robert de Arundell, Baron of Arundell before 1100, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1075–1150":"1075–1150","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1105–Female":"1105–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1105":"1105","before 1100":"enne 1100","1100":"1100","Abt 1105":"umbes 1105","1075":"1075","1150":"1150","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Europe":"Europe","Poorstock, Bridport, Dorset, England":"Bridport, Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1075–1150":"1075–1150","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","1105–Female":"1105–Kuollut","–Female